{
  "card_id": "breakout",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Breakout",
  "aliases": [
    "Breakout Signature",
    "breakout signature",
    "突破"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price move that aggressively closes beyond a previous swing high or low out of a consolidation or retracement, signaling continuation. Identified by closure (not just a wick) above/below the prior range high or low, followed by expansive directional candles with shallow opposing retracements. Requires continuation confirmation to avoid false breakouts.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price must close beyond the previous swing high (bullish) or swing low (bearish), not merely wick through it.",
    "The breakout closure should emerge from a consolidation or shallow retracement that follows a prior expansion leg.",
    "Following the breakout closure, expect large-range expansion candles with very shallow retracements against the move.",
    "A new opposing candle (protected swing) forming intraday after retesting the opening price confirms the breakout structure.",
    "Distinguish from a consolidation manipulation: a true breakout produces follow-through expansion, not a sweep that reverts back inside the range.",
    "If the breakout takes out a short-term high or low, wait for further continuation to confirm validity."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "A breakout closure signals continuation and is used to anticipate expansive moves with shallow retracements. Traders mark the breakout level and previous day high/low as references, hold positions as long as price respects the breakout area, and track protected swings to manage risk. After roughly three days of expansion into an objective, reassess for retracement, reversal, or consolidation. Avoid entering solely on price crossing the boundary; wait for continuation confirmation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating a sweep of the prior high/low as a breakout when price did not actually close above it (no closure = no protected swing).",
    "Expecting continued expansion after three days of breakout-driven expansion into an objective instead of anticipating a new phase of price.",
    "Confusing a consolidation manipulation (sweep and revert) with a genuine breakout closure with follow-through.",
    "Entering immediately when price crosses the consolidation boundary without waiting for continuation confirmation.",
    "Mistaking a short-term high/low taken out after the breakout as valid continuation, leading to entry before reversal."
  ],
  "related_concepts": [],
  "merge_strategy": "llm_synthesis",
  "merge_model": "deepseek/deepseek-chat",
  "merge_notes": "School conflict: ICT vs Price Action; picked ICT by majority (1 ICT, 1 Price Action). The ICT card emphasized continuation confirmation; the Price Action card added closure and protected swing details. Both definitions merged.",
